{
  "texts": [
    "Constraintbased algorithms which take account of latent confounders and selection variables generally produce a PAG.",
    "There are three types of endpoint possible at each end of an edge in a PAG:",
    "• an invariant arrowhead, marked as \">\", indicating that all MAGs in the equivalence class have an arrowhead at that endpoint; • an invariant tail, marked as \"-\", indicating that all MAGs in the equivalence class have a tail at that endpoint; • a variant endpoint, marked as \"o\", indicating that some MAGs in the equivalence class have an arrowhead, and others a tail, at that endpoint.",
    "So, for example, an edge • → in a PAG indicates that MAGs in the equivalence class may have → or ↔ at that location, and similarly an edge • -• in the PAG indicates that MAGs in the equivalence class can have a →, ←, ↔ oredge at that location.",
    "Note that the semantics of CPDAGs and PAGs are somewhat different."
  ]
}